======================================================================
PART 3: REED-MULLER CODE CONNECTION
  H(T) has degree d = 2*floor((n-1)/2) [Degree Drop Theorem]
  So H is in RM(d, m) — the Reed-Muller code of order d on m variables
  RM(d,m) has dimension sum_{k=0}^{d} C(m,k)
======================================================================

  n=3: degree d=2
    Arc variables: m=3, RM(2,3) dim = 7
    Tiling variables: m_tiling=1, RM(2,1) dim = 2
    Total tournaments: 2^3 = 8
    H values from 8 tournaments: at most 8 (in practice much fewer)

  n=4: degree d=2
    Arc variables: m=6, RM(2,6) dim = 22
    Tiling variables: m_tiling=3, RM(2,3) dim = 7
    Total tournaments: 2^6 = 64
    H values from 64 tournaments: at most 64 (in practice much fewer)

  n=5: degree d=4
    Arc variables: m=10, RM(4,10) dim = 386
    Tiling variables: m_tiling=6, RM(4,6) dim = 57
    Total tournaments: 2^10 = 1024
    H values from 1024 tournaments: at most 1024 (in practice much fewer)

  n=6: degree d=4
    Arc variables: m=15, RM(4,15) dim = 1941
    Tiling variables: m_tiling=10, RM(4,10) dim = 386
    Total tournaments: 2^15 = 32768
    H values from 32768 tournaments: at most 32768 (in practice much fewer)

======================================================================
PART 4: STRIP STRUCTURE AND TILING CODES
  Strip Str(k) = {(r,c) : r+c=k, r,c >= 1} has k-1 tiles
  Strips are the 'rows' of the triangular grid (anti-diagonals)
======================================================================

  n=5:
    Strip 2 (1 tiles): [(3, 1)]
    Strip 3 (2 tiles): [(4, 2), (4, 1)]
    Strip 4 (3 tiles): [(5, 3), (5, 2), (5, 1)]

  Strip weight profiles for GS tilings:
    strips=[0, 0, 0]: H values = [1]
    strips=[0, 0, 1]: H values = [9]
    strips=[0, 1, 0]: H values = [3]
    strips=[0, 1, 1]: H values = [13, 15]
    strips=[0, 1, 2]: H values = [15]
    strips=[0, 2, 1]: H values = [9]
    strips=[0, 2, 2]: H values = [11]
    strips=[1, 0, 1]: H values = [9]
    strips=[1, 0, 2]: H values = [13]
    strips=[1, 1, 1]: H values = [11]
    strips=[1, 1, 2]: H values = [15]
    strips=[1, 1, 3]: H values = [13]
    strips=[1, 2, 2]: H values = [11]
    strips=[1, 2, 3]: H values = [9]

  n=7:
    Strip 2 (1 tiles): [(3, 1)]
    Strip 3 (2 tiles): [(4, 2), (4, 1)]
    Strip 4 (3 tiles): [(5, 3), (5, 2), (5, 1)]
    Strip 5 (4 tiles): [(6, 4), (6, 3), (6, 2), (6, 1)]
    Strip 6 (5 tiles): [(7, 5), (7, 4), (7, 3), (7, 2), (7, 1)]

======================================================================
PART 5: BLUE LINE SKELETON AND TANNER GRAPHS
  In coding theory, the Tanner graph connects variable nodes to
  check nodes. Does the skeleton have this structure?
======================================================================

  n=5: 16 GS tilings -> 7 classes
    (np.int64(0), np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(3), np.int64(4)), c3=0, H=1: 1 GS tilings
    (np.int64(0), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(4)), c3=1, H=3: 1 GS tilings
    (np.int64(1), np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(3), np.int64(3)), c3=3, H=9: 4 GS tilings
    (np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(3)), c3=4, H=11: 3 GS tilings
    (np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(3)), c3=4, H=13: 3 GS tilings
    (np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(3)), c3=4, H=15: 1 GS tilings
    (np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2)), c3=5, H=15: 3 GS tilings

  Skeleton edges (GS flip between different classes):
    ((np.int64(0), np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(3), np.int64(4)), 0, 1) <-> ((np.int64(1), np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(3), np.int64(3)), 3, 9)
    ((np.int64(0), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(4)), 1, 3) <-> ((np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(3)), 4, 13)
    ((np.int64(1), np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(3), np.int64(3)), 3, 9) <-> ((np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(3)), 4, 11)
    ((np.int64(1), np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(3), np.int64(3)), 3, 9) <-> ((np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(3)), 4, 13)
    ((np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(3)), 4, 11) <-> ((np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2)), 5, 15)
    ((np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(3)), 4, 13) <-> ((np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2)), 5, 15)
    ((np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(3)), 4, 15) <-> ((np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2)), 5, 15)

  t3 parity bipartition check:
    ((np.int64(0), np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(3), np.int64(4)), 0, 1): t3=0 -> side EVEN
    ((np.int64(0), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(4)), 1, 3): t3=1 -> side ODD
    ((np.int64(1), np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(3), np.int64(3)), 3, 9): t3=3 -> side ODD
    ((np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(3)), 4, 11): t3=4 -> side EVEN
    ((np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(3)), 4, 13): t3=4 -> side EVEN
    ((np.int64(1), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(3)), 4, 15): t3=4 -> side EVEN
    ((np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2), np.int64(2)), 5, 15): t3=5 -> side ODD

  Skeleton bipartite (t3 parity)? True

======================================================================
PART 6: HAMMING WEIGHT = BACKWARD ARC COUNT
  The Hamming weight of a tiling = # backward (blue) arcs
  = # arcs pointing 'against' the base path direction
  This is related to the 'writhe' from knot theory (S69)
======================================================================

  n=5: Hamming weight (backward arcs) vs H:
    hw= 0: mean H=  1.00, H range=[1,1], count=1
    hw= 1: mean H=  4.67, H range=[3,9], count=6
    hw= 2: mean H=  8.33, H range=[5,15], count=15
    hw= 3: mean H= 11.00, H range=[5,15], count=20
    hw= 4: mean H= 12.07, H range=[9,15], count=15
    hw= 5: mean H= 11.33, H range=[9,13], count=6
    hw= 6: mean H=  9.00, H range=[9,9], count=1

  Mean H by Hamming weight (should be symmetric):
    hw= 0: mean H =   1.00 #
    hw= 1: mean H =   4.67 ####
    hw= 2: mean H =   8.33 ########
    hw= 3: mean H =  11.00 ###########
    hw= 4: mean H =  12.07 ############
    hw= 5: mean H =  11.33 ###########
    hw= 6: mean H =   9.00 #########

